> The first principle I would use is data minimization. Every data element requested should map to a specific customer benefit or product capability.

For example, if a budgeting app needs transaction history to categorize spending, that is directly tied to the service being provided. However, if the same app requests investment holdings, mortgage information, or several years of transaction history, I would ask what customer outcome requires that data.

Second, I would evaluate proportionality. Is the amount, frequency, and duration of data access aligned with the service being delivered? Sometimes aggregated balances are sufficient, while other use cases may require detailed transaction data.

Third, I would ensure transparency and consent. Customers should clearly understand what data is being shared, why it is needed, how long it will be retained, and whether it will be used for purposes beyond the requested service.

Finally, I would establish governance controls through data-sharing agreements, audits, monitoring, and periodic reviews to ensure the vendor continues using the data only for the approved purpose.

Ultimately, my test is simple: if I cannot clearly explain to a customer why each data element is necessary and how it benefits them, then we are likely over-sharing.




